[133.588118, "o", "                                                                          \r\n\u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m  \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;185;192;171m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m 18 \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198mBoth are consumer hardware companies launching home video game consoles with a proprietary first-party game library and a third-party developer licensing program вЂ”\u001b[18;170H the exact model Atari invented and repeatedly attempted. The structural challenge is identical: achieving hardwa\r\n\u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m  \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;185;192;171m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m    \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198mre critical mass to attract third-party developers, whose content in turn drives hardware sales, a classic two-sided platform cold-start problem. Atari's repeated failures (5200 incompatibility, Jaguar under-library, Lynx supply shortage, VCS crowdfunding delays) are a direct\r\n\u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m  \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;185;192;171m\u001b[48;2;232;220;198m    \u001b(B\u001b[m\u001b[38;2;62;71;77m\u001b[48"]
